{
  "solution": "For a Hohmann transfer between two circular orbits, the transfer orbit is an ellipse with periapsis at the lower orbit radius and apoapsis at the higher orbit radius. The specific mechanical energy ε of an orbit is given by ε = -μ / (2a), where μ is the gravitational parameter of Earth (μ = 398600 km³/s²) and a is the semi-major axis of the orbit. For the transfer ellipse, the semi-major axis a_t is the average of the periapsis distance r_p and apoapsis distance r_a: a_t = (r_p + r_a) / 2. Here, the initial orbit radius is larger, so r_a = 7412.1 km and r_p = 6690.6 km. Thus, a_t = (6690.6 + 7412.1) / 2 = 14102.7 / 2 = 7051.35 km. Then, ε_t = -μ / (2a_t) = -398600 / (2 * 7051.35) = -398600 / 14102.7 ≈ -28.265 km²/s².",
