Step1: According to the stellar number-density formula of the Milky Way:  

$n(z, R) = n_0 \left( e^{-z/z_{\text{thin}}} + e^{-z/z_{\text{thick}}} \right) e^{-R/h_R}$

where $z_{\text{thin}} = 90\,\text{pc}$, $z_{\text{thick}} = 1000\,\text{pc}$, $h_R = 2.25\,\text{kpc}$, and $n_0 \sim 0.02\,\text{pc}^{-3}$.  
For this problem, substitute the numerical values.

Get:

$n(0,3) = n_0 \left( e^{-0/z_{\text{thin}}} + e^{-0/z_{\text{thick}}} \right) e^{-3/2.25}
       = 0.02 \times 2 \times e^{-3/2.25}
       \approx 0.0057\,\text{pc}^{-3}$

Step2: Substitute the remaining specific values from the problem.

Get:

$\begin{cases}
n(0, 15) = 2.76 \times 10^{-5}\,\text{pc}^{-3} \\
n(0.1, 8) = 2.3 \times 10^{-4}\,\text{pc}^{-3} \\
n(1, 8) = 1.79 \times 10^{-5}\,\text{pc}^{-3}
\end{cases}$

